04819nam a22005415i 9780814765210DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147652107 a10.18574/nyu/9780814765210.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)679306  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0280002bisacsh00aNew Versions of Victims :bFeminists Struggle with the Concept /ced. by Sharon Lamb. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- t1. Heretical Texts: The Courage to Heal and the Incest Survivor Movement -- t2. The Challenge to Feminism Posed by Women's Use of Violence in Intimate Relationships -- t3. "I Wasn't Raped, but . . . ": Revisiting Definitional Problems in Sexual Victimization -- t4. Recasting Consent: Agency and Victimization in Adult-Teen Relationships -- t5. Constructing the Victim: Popular Images and Lasting Labels -- t6. In the Line of Sight at Public Eye: In Search of a Victim -- t7. Trauma Talk in Feminist Clinical Practice -- t8. Victims, Backlash, and Radical Feminist Theory (or, The Morning after They Stole Feminism's Fire) -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIt is increasingly difficult to use the word "victim" these days without facing either ridicule for "crying victim" or criticism for supposed harshness toward those traumatized. Some deny the possibility of "recovering" repressed memories of abuse, or consider date rape an invention of whining college students. At the opposite extreme, others contend that women who experience abuse are "survivors" likely destined to be psychically wounded for life. While the debates rage between victims' rights advocates and "backlash" authors, the contributors to New Versions of Victims collectively argue that we must move beyond these polarizations to examine the "victim" as a socially constructed term and to explore, in nuanced terms, why we see victims the way we do. Must one have been subject to extreme or prolonged suffering to merit designation as a victim? How are we to explain rape victims who seemingly "get over" their experience with no lingering emotional scars? Resisting the reductive oversimplifications of the polemicists, the contributors to New Versions of Victims critique exaggerated claims by victim advocates about the harm of victimization while simultaneously taking on the reactionary boilerplate of writers such as Katie Roiphe and Camille Paglia and offering further strategies for countering the backlash. Written in clear, accessible language, New Versions of Victims offers a critical analysis of popular debates about victimization that will be applicable to both practice and theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAtmore, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGavey, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaaken, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamb, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamb, Sharon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarecek, Jeanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Lynn M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRenzetti, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRonai, Carol Rambo, econtributor.4ctb4h